#install.packages("vars") 
#install.packages("astsa") 
library(vars)
library(astsa)

#creates a vector of response variables
x = cbind(cmort, tempr, part) 

#VAR command does estimation of AR models using ordinary least squares while simultaneously fitting the trend, intercept, and ARIMA model
plot.ts(x , main = "", xlab = "")

fitvar1= VAR(x, p=1, type="both")
summary(fitvar1)

# Removing NAs
hilo2015[is.na(hilo2015)] <- 0
sum(is.na(hilo2015))
[1] 0
# Saving as numeric vectors
riverflow <- as.numeric(hilo2015$cms)
chlorophyll <- as.numeric(hilo2015$ChlRF)
Unknown or uninitialised column: `ChlRF`.
dissolved_o2 <- as.numeric(hilo2015$Doper)
salinity <- as.numeric(hilo2015$saltppt)
temp <- as.numeric(hilo2015$TempC)
turbidity <- as.numeric(hilo2015$Corr.NTU)

#creates a vector of response variables
h_chlorophyll <-  cbind(riverflow, chlorophyll)
h_dissolvedo2 <- cbind(riverflow, dissolved_o2)
h_salinity <- cbind(riverflow, salinity)
h_temp <- cbind(riverflow, temp)
h_turbidity <- cbind(riverflow, turbidity)

#VAR command does estimation of AR models using ordinary least squares while simultaneously fitting the trend, intercept, and ARIMA model
#plot.ts(h , main = "", xlab = "")
fitvar1_chlorophyll= VAR(h_chlorophyll, p=1, type="both")
Error in VAR(h_chlorophyll, p = 1, type = "both") : 
  The matrix 'y' should contain at least two variables. For univariate analysis consider ar() and arima() in package stats.
# 2nd Lag
fitvar2.salt = VAR(h_salinity, p=2, type="both")
summary(fitvar2.salt)
